Definitions for all error codes.

enum IonicSecurity::SDK::ErrorCode
strong

Enumeration that represents error codes from the C++ SDK.

Enumerator
AGENT_OK 

Success code.

AGENT_ERROR 

A general error occurred, but its specific problem is not represented with its own code.

AGENT_UNKNOWN 

An unknown and unexpected error occurred.

AGENT_NOMEMORY 

A memory allocation failed.

This can happen if there is not a sufficient amount of memory available to perform an operation.

AGENT_MISSINGVALUE 

An expected and required value was not found.

This is typically emitted from functions that are responsible for parsing / deserializing data.

AGENT_INVALIDVALUE 

A value was found that is invalid.

For example, a string value was expected, but it was actually an integer. This is typically emitted from functions that are responsible for parsing / deserializing data.

AGENT_NOINIT 

The agent was used before being initialized.

Make sure that you call Agent::Initialize, Agent::InitializeWithoutProfiles, or another initialization function before trying to use the Agent object.

AGENT_DOUBLEINIT 

Agent initialization was performed twice.

This will happen if you try calling one of the agent initialization functions after it has already been initialized.

AGENT_CREATEFINGERPRINT 

Fingerprint creation failed.

AGENT_REQUESTFAILED 

A network request failed.

A request failed due to connection failure, unknown server, unresponsive server, or other network problem.

AGENT_PARSEFAILED 

The parsing of some serialized data failed.

This typically happens if a file or block of data is corrupted or of an unexpected format.

AGENT_UNEXPECTEDRESPONSE 

A server replied with a response that the agent was not expecting.

This can happen if the server rejects a request, it doesn't support the API version used by the agent, etc.

AGENT_BADCONFIG 

The agent configuration is invalid.

This could be because the HTTP implementation is not recognized, the server hostname/IP is empty, etc.

AGENT_OPENFILE 

A file failed to open.

This normally happens because the file path provided does not exist or it is not accessible due to lack of permission.

AGENT_BADREQUEST 

The request object is invalid.

The request object failed validation in the agent code. This can happen if any of the request data is not acceptable (e.g. empty key ID, required properties missing).

AGENT_BADRESPONSE 

The response object is invalid.

The response object failed validation in the agent code. This means that the server responseded with an invalid / unacceptable response.

AGENT_BADREDIRECT 

The server redirected the agent to an invalid location (e.g. an empty URL)

This is typically indicative that there is a problem on the server side.

AGENT_TOOMANYREDIRECTS 

The maximum amount of allowed server redirects has been hit.

The server redirected us too many times. The maximum number of allowed redirects can be set during Agent initialization via AgentConfig::MaxRedirects.

AGENT_NOTIMPLEMENTED 

The function (or a function it depends on) is not implemented.

AGENT_NOTALLOWED 

The function (or a function it depends on) is not allowed to be called.

This typically happens if the function would knowingly cause a problem if it were to be run.

AGENT_TIMEOUT 

An operation has timed out.

This happens when a blocking function has been used with a maximum wait time, and that time has expired.

AGENT_NULL_INPUT 

A null pointer was passed to a function that does not accept null pointers.

AGENT_NO_DEVICE_PROFILE 

An active device profile has not been set.

This happens when a function is called that requires an active device profile, but there is no profile set yet (e.g. Agent::CreateKeys()).

AGENT_RESOURCE_NOT_FOUND 

A resource was not found.

This happens when attempting to access a resource that does not exist.

AGENT_KEY_DENIED 

A request to create or fetch a key was denied by the server.

AGENT_FPHASH_DENIED 

A request was denied because there was a fingerprint hash mismatch.

AGENT_FPFULL_DENIED 

A request was denied because the full fingerprint was denied.

AGENT_CID_TIMESTAMP_DENIED 

A request was denied because the conversation ID (CID) timestamp was denied.

AGENT_NO_PROFILE_PERSISTOR 

No default profile persistor is available for the current platform. A profile persistor must be specified.

AGENT_LOAD_PROFILES_FAILED 

Failed to load device profiles.

This may happen if an incorrect password was provided, the storage file is corrupt, or some other problem occurred.

AGENT_INVALID_KEY 

A key is invalid in some way (key ID, key bytes, etc).

This may happen if a key was found to be invalid. For example, if the key is the wrong size (any size other than 32 bytes), the key ID string is empty or contains invalid characters, etc.

AGENT_STALE_KEY_ATTRIBUTES 

Key updated failed because key attribute data is stale.

AGENT_DUPLICATE_KEY 

A keys update request contains two or more entries with the same key id.

This is a user error.

AGENT_HEADER_NOT_FOUND 

A header was not found in the specified data.

This may happen if the data version is older and special handling for this error may be necessary to support previous SDK versions existing on the system.

AGENT_NO_SECURE_CONNECTION 

An HTTPS secure connection was not achieved.

This commonly happens when the device OS is either setup without TLS 1.x, or is intentionally set to use a weaker security standard. Ionic servers require at least TLS 1.0.

CHUNKCRYPTO_OK 

Success code.

CHUNKCRYPTO_ERROR 

A general error occurred, but its specific problem is not represented with its own code.

CHUNKCRYPTO_UNKNOWN 

An unknown and unexpected error occurred.

CHUNKCRYPTO_NOMEMORY 

A memory allocation failed.

This can happen if there is not a sufficient amount of memory available to perform an operation.

CHUNKCRYPTO_MISSINGVALUE 

An expected and required value was not found.

This is typically emitted from functions that are responsible for parsing / deserializing data.

CHUNKCRYPTO_INVALIDVALUE 

A value was found that is invalid.

For example, a string value was expected, but it was actually an integer. This is typically emitted from functions that are responsible for parsing / deserializing data.

CHUNKCRYPTO_NULL_INPUT 

A null pointer was passed to a function that does not accept null pointers.

CHUNKCRYPTO_BAD_INPUT 

An invalid input value was encountered.

An input value was found that is invalid. For example, a buffer length input was equal to zero.

CHUNKCRYPTO_EOF 

The end of a data chunk was found before it was expected.

This normally happens if the data chunk has been truncated or is zero length.

CHUNKCRYPTO_PARSEFAILED 

The parsing of some serialized data failed.

This typically happens if a file or block of data is corrupted or of an unexpected format.

CHUNKCRYPTO_HASH_VERIFICATION 

A hash digest verification failed.

The computed digest did not match the expected digest.

CHUNKCRYPTO_STREAM_WRITE 

A failure occurred while writing to a stream.

An error flag of some sort was set on the stream when it was being written to.

CHUNKCRYPTO_RESOURCE_NOT_FOUND 

A resource was not found.

This happens when attempting to access a resource that does not exist.

CHUNKCRYPTO_UNRECOGNIZED 

A data chunk is not supported for Ionic protection.

CHUNKCRYPTO_ALREADY_ENCRYPTED 

A data chunk was requested to be encrypted, but it is already encrypted.

CHUNKCRYPTO_NOT_ENCRYPTED 

A data chunk was requested to be decrypted, but it is not encrypted.

CRYPTO_OK 

Success code.

CRYPTO_ERROR 

A general error occurred, but its specific problem is not represented with its own code.

CRYPTO_UNKNOWN 

An unknown and unexpected error occurred.

CRYPTO_NULL_INPUT 

A null pointer was passed to one of the crypto functions.

CRYPTO_BAD_INPUT 

An invalid input value was encountered.

An input value was found that is invalid. For example, a buffer length input was equal to zero.

CRYPTO_NO_INIT 

CryptoAbstract module has not been initialized.

The crypto module was used before being initialized via Crypto::Initialize().

CRYPTO_NOMEMORY 

Memory allocation error.

This can happen if there is not a sufficient amount of memory available to perform an operation.

CRYPTO_KEY_VALIDATION 

Key validation error.

A key was loaded or generated that did not pass validation. For example, this may happen when loading or generating an RSA private key.

CRYPTO_BAD_SIGNATURE 

Message signature verification error.

A message signature verification failed. This can be returned by RSA signature verification functions.

CRYPTO_SEED_OVERFLOW 

A seed overflow occurred during RSA private key generation.

During RSA private key generation, it is possible for the random seed to overflow (although extremely unlikely). In that situation, RSA key generation is aborted and the CRYPTO_RSA_SEED_OVERFLOW error code is returned.

When this error is encountered, it is recommended to simply try again.

CRYPTO_FATAL 

Fatal error.

A fatal error has occurred and the module will no longer be usable. This will happen if any POST test, healthcheck test, or any other operational test fails at any time. such failure of any test indicates the possibility of the module being compromised, and so it becomes disabled.

FILECRYPTO_OK 

Success code.

FILECRYPTO_ERROR 

A general error occurred, but its specific problem is not represented with its own code.

FILECRYPTO_UNKNOWN 

An unknown and unexpected error occurred.

FILECRYPTO_NOMEMORY 

A memory allocation failed.

This can happen if there is not a sufficient amount of memory available to perform an operation.

FILECRYPTO_MISSINGVALUE 

An expected and required value was not found.

This is typically emitted from functions that are responsible for parsing / deserializing data.

FILECRYPTO_INVALIDVALUE 

A value was found that is invalid.

For example, a string value was expected, but it was actually an integer. This is typically emitted from functions that are responsible for parsing / deserializing data.

FILECRYPTO_NULL_INPUT 

A null pointer was passed to a function that does not accept null pointers.

FILECRYPTO_BAD_INPUT 

An invalid input value was encountered.

An input value was found that is invalid. For example, a buffer length input was equal to zero.

FILECRYPTO_OPENFILE 

A file failed to open.

This normally happens because the file path provided does not exist or it is not accessible due to lack of permission.

FILECRYPTO_EOF 

The end of a file was found before it was expected.

This normally happens if the file has been truncated or is zero length.

FILECRYPTO_NOHEADER 

A file header could not be found where it was expected.

This normally happens when trying to decrypt a file that is not encrypted, or the encrypted file has been corrupted.

FILECRYPTO_PARSEFAILED 

The parsing of some serialized data failed.

This typically happens if a file or block of data is corrupted or of an unexpected format.

FILECRYPTO_VERSION_UNSUPPORTED 

The file version is unsupported or unrecognized.

FILECRYPTO_HASH_VERIFICATION 

A hash digest verification failed.

The computed digest did not match the expected digest.

FILECRYPTO_STREAM_WRITE 

A failure occurred while writing to a stream.

An error flag of some sort was set on the stream when it was being written to.

FILECRYPTO_RESOURCE_NOT_FOUND 

A resource was not found.

This happens when attempting to access a resource that does not exist.

FILECRYPTO_BAD_ZIP 

A zip file failed to open because it was not formatted correctly.

This normally happens because the zip file is corrupted in some way (for example truncated).

FILECRYPTO_UNRECOGNIZED 

A file is not supported for Ionic protection.

FILECRYPTO_ALREADY_ENCRYPTED 

A file was requested to be encrypted, but it is already encrypted.

FILECRYPTO_NOT_ENCRYPTED 

A file was requested to be decrypted, but it is not encrypted.

FILECRYPTO_RENAMEFILE 

A file failed to be renamed.

This normally happens because a temporary file was attempted to be renamed in order to overwrite an input file during in-place encryption or decryption, but the rename attempt failed (see FileCipherAbstract::Encrypt(const String^)). A system level error code is emitted to the logger in this case.

The file may be open by another process or by another thread in the current process, you may not have permissions to write to the file, or some other error occurred.

FILECRYPTO_NOEMBED 

A file did not contain an Ionic embed stream.

FILECRYPTO_NO_COVERPAGE 

A file type was specified that does not have a cover page.

FILECRYPTO_IOSTREAM_ERROR 

An error occurred in the Streams lib. The user should check 'errno' and/or 'strerror(errno)' for details.

FINGERPRINT_OK 

Success code.

FINGERPRINT_ERROR 

A general error occurred, but its specific problem is not represented with its own code.

FINGERPRINT_UNKNOWN 

An unknown and unexpected error occurred.

FINGERPRINT_NOMEMORY 

A memory allocation failed.

This can happen if there is not a sufficient amount of memory available to perform an operation.

KEYVAULT_OK 

Success code.

KEYVAULT_ERROR_BASE 

Error code range base.

KEYVAULT_ERROR 

A general error occurred, but its specific problem is not represented with its own code.

KEYVAULT_UNKNOWN 

An unknown and unexpected error occurred.

KEYVAULT_NOMEMORY 

A memory allocation failed.

This can happen if there is not a sufficient amount of memory available to perform an operation.

KEYVAULT_MISSINGVALUE 

An expected and required value was not found.

This is typically emitted from functions that are responsible for parsing / deserializing data.

KEYVAULT_INVALIDVALUE 

A value was found that is invalid.

For example, a string value was expected, but it was actually an integer. This is typically emitted from functions that are responsible for parsing / deserializing data.

KEYVAULT_KEY_NOT_FOUND 

A key was not found.

This happens when attempting to access a key that does not exist, for example when trying to retrieve via ISKeyVault::getKey() or update a key via ISKeyVault::setKey().

KEYVAULT_KEY_UPDATE_IGNORED 

A key update request was ignored.

This happens when attempting to update a key via ISKeyVault::setKey(), and the provided key is not newer than the key which already exists in the vault. This is not an error, per se, but it is informing the caller that the requested update is not needed, and as such is ignored. The determination is made by comparing key issuance UTC time (ISKeyVaultKey::getIssuedServerTimeUtcSeconds()).

KEYVAULT_OPENFILE 

A file failed to open.

This normally happens because the file path provided does not exist or it is not accessible due to lack of permission.

KEYVAULT_EOF 

The end of a file was found before it was expected.

This normally happens if the file has been truncated or is zero length.

KEYVAULT_NOHEADER 

A file header could not be found where it was expected.

This normally happens when trying to decrypt a file that is not encrypted, or the encrypted file has been corrupted.

KEYVAULT_PARSEFAILED 

The parsing of some serialized data failed.

This typically happens if a file or block of data is corrupted or of an unexpected format.

KEYVAULT_HEADER_MISMATCH 

A key vault file header has values which were not expected.

This typically happens when a key vault attempts to open a file that was saved by a different key vault type. For example, if a Windows DPAPI key vault object attempts to open a file that was saved by a different key vault type (e.g. Apple Keychain key vault).

KEYVAULT_LOAD_NOT_NEEDED 

A key vault load operation was skipped because it was not needed.

This happens when a load operation is requested on a key vault, but the vault skipped the operation because it determined that the underlying storage data has not changed since the previous load operation. A key vault may do this in order to optimize execution time by avoiding costly loads from disk when possible.

KEYVAULT_CREATE_PATH 

A key vault save operation could not create the required file path.

This happens when a save operation is requested on a key vault, but the vault is unable to create the necessary folder path to store the file. For example, if the destination file path is /a/b/c/vault.dat, and the folder /a/b/c does not exist (or some part of it), then the key vault attempts to create the path. If the path cannot be created, then ISKEYVAULT_CREATE_PATH is returned.

KEYVAULT_INVALID_KEY 

A key is invalid in some way (key ID, key bytes, etc).

This may happen if a key was found to be invalid. For example, if the key is the wrong size (any size other than 32 bytes), the key ID string is empty or contains invalid characters, etc.

KEYVAULT_RESOURCE_NOT_FOUND 

A resource was not found.

This happens when attempting to access a resource that does not exist.

KEYVAULT_FILE_VERSION 

A key vault file load operation failed due to unsupported file version.

This happens when a key vault attempts to load a file from disk, but the version of that file is not supported. This may happen when an older version of the SDK is used to load a file that was saved by a newer version of the SDK.
